me of the most distinguished scholars in the field to offer a new perspective for the study of religion, one that examines the works of transmission and innovation through the prism of learning. They argue that religious culture is socially and dynamically constructed by agents who are not mere passive recipients but engaged in active learning processes. Finding a middle way between the social and the cognitive, they see learning religions not as a mechanism of “downloading” but also as a social process with its relational dimension.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 07. Nov 2022) 0aAnthropology of religionvCongresses. 0aEthnologyxReligious aspectsvCongresses. 0aReligionvCongresses. 7aRELIGION / General.2bisacsh1 aBerliner, David, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBerliner, David, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aDonzelli, Aurora, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGoldman, Marcio, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHouseman, Michael, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHérault, Laurence, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLambek, Michael, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLuhrmann, T. M., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aParkin, David, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRowlands, Michael, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSarró, Ramon, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSarró, Ramon, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aSeveri, Carlo, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aStafford, Charles, econtributor.4ctb4ht